The paper deals with efficient distributed computation in dynamic networks, which is a topic that falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The use of random walks as a tool for designing distributed algorithms suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). The paper also discusses the decentralized computation of spectral properties, which is a topic that falls under the sub-category of Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI). The use of random walks and spectral properties also suggests that the paper may be relevant to the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Machine Learning (cs.LG).
